      "rationale": "Three-level mesh refinement study conducted on the screw-rod-vertebral body assembly; construct stiffness QoI changed by 1.4% between medium and fine meshes. Richardson extrapolation GCI of 0.8% reported, confirming discretization error is negligible relative to the 10% acceptance bound."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Numerical solver error",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Iterative solver residuals and contact force equilibrium verified at each load step; Newton-Raphson convergence criteria documented.",
      "rationale": "Nonlinear static analyses used Newton-Raphson iteration with force residual tolerance 0.1% and displacement tolerance 0.5%. Contact force balance verified at final load step across all 11 model instances; maximum force imbalance 0.07%, well within tolerance."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Use error",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Independent peer review of model setup, boundary conditions, and material assignments conducted by analyst not involved in original model development.",
      "rationale": "A second licensed FEA analyst independently reviewed the model input files, boundary condition definitions, material property assignments, and contact pair definitions. Two minor discrepancies identified and corrected prior to final simulation runs; corrected model re-reviewed and approved."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Model form",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Constitutive model selection justified by material characterization data; contact formulation appropriate for frictional screw-rod interface.",
      "rationale": "Ti-6Al-4V screw and rod modeled as bilinear isotropic hardening using tensile coupon data from the same material lot. UHMWPE vertebral body surrogate modeled as elastic-perfectly-plastic consistent with published material characterization. Augmented Lagrange contact with friction coefficient 0.2 (measured value) used at screw-rod interface; formulation validated against slip-load bench data."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Model inputs",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "All material properties and geometric dimensions sourced from traceable measurements; uncertainty in inputs propagated to QoI uncertainty.",
      "rationale": "Screw and rod geometry digitized from coordinate measuring machine data (±0.01 mm). Material properties derived from lot-specific tensile testing (n=5 coupons). Monte Carlo propagation of input uncertainties (geometry ±0.5%, modulus ±3%, yield strength ±2%) yielded combined QoI uncertainty of ±4.1%, included in validation metric calculation."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Test samples",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Test constructs drawn from production lot; sample size sufficient for statistical comparison; dimensional inspection confirms conformance to nominal geometry.",
      "rationale": "N=11 constructs assembled from production-released screws and rods (same lot as CMM-measured geometry). All constructs dimensionally inspected; all within ±0.05 mm of nominal. Sample size provides 80% power to detect a 10% mean difference at alpha=0.05, satisfying pre-specified statistical requirement."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Test conditions",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Test conditions span the range of clinically relevant loading scenarios including at least two load levels or construct configurations.",
      "rationale": "Testing conducted under a single ASTM F1717 compression-bending configuration at a single load rate (5 mm/min) in ambient laboratory environment. While this fully replicates the regulatory standard, only one test condition was applied. This factor achieves Gradation 2 rather than the required Gradation 3; accepted based on regulatory precedent and the deterministic nature of the ASTM protocol, with the shortfall documented as a known limitation of the validation scope."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Equivalency of input parameters",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Model input parameters demonstrably equivalent to test conditions; any differences quantified and their effect on QoI bounded.",
      "rationale": "Boundary conditions in the FEA (fixed inferior vertebral body, displacement-controlled superior loading block) replicate the test fixture kinematics. Fixture compliance measured (0.12 N/mm) and incorporated into model. Ambient temperature assumed identical; no thermal effects modeled. Residual assembly torque not modeled; sensitivity analysis shows <1.5% effect on stiffness QoI."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Output comparison",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Validation metric E/uval < 1.96 for all three QoIs; percent difference < 10% for all QoIs.",
      "rationale": "Construct stiffness: FEA 312.4 N/mm vs bench mean 308.1 N/mm (1.4% difference, E/uval 0.61). Yield force: FEA 1847 N vs bench mean 1821 N (1.4% difference, E/uval 0.83). Force at 40 mm: FEA 2103 N vs bench mean 2078 N (1.2% difference, E/uval 0.74). All three QoIs satisfy both acceptance criteria across both laboratories."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Relevance of the quantities of interest",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "QoIs directly linked to the COU decision; clinical and regulatory relevance of each QoI documented.",
      "rationale": "Construct stiffness, yield force, and force at 40 mm displacement are the three QoIs specified in ASTM F1717 and FDA guidance for pedicle screw 510(k) submissions. Each QoI maps directly to a failure mode relevant to the COU (construct loosening, screw yielding, gross construct failure). Relevance chain from QoI to clinical risk documented in the hazard analysis."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Relevance of the validation activities to the COU",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Validation scenario matches COU geometry, loading, and material system; any differences between validation and COU contexts identified and bounded.",
      "rationale": "Validation conducted on the identical screw design, rod diameter, and UHMWPE surrogate specified in the COU. ASTM F1717 test configuration directly matches the intended regulatory submission context. The validation scenario is therefore judged fully congruent with the COU; no extrapolation beyond the validated domain is required for the submission decision."
    }
